narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learnt a great deal about the Romantic poets, especially Wordsworth, Keats and Shelley.
I learnt a lot about the romantic poets and the different ways to approach romantic poetry, such as from an anti-romantic perspective versus a romantic perspective.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The course was extremely difficult but also extremely interesting since the professor is very illustrious. The grades given are very low compared to other English classes I have taken at Yale. The class discussions are sometimes quite difficult and demoralizing, since the readings are very long and we only focus on around two lines of the text at a time.

The discussion is usually good and Professor Brisman is great. He has a wonderful mind and is clearly very passionate about romantic poetry. It would have been nice to have more opportunity for student engagement beyond discussion.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: It was a meaningful exercise in challenging my own understanding of how to write literary criticism, but I am not sure if I would recommend it to another student. It is very difficult and abstract. The professor is very kind, understanding and well-versed.

Yes, if you like English and want to learn more about romantic poetry. The topics are quite dense and some of the poetry is obscure, but that is often the point and we spend most of class parsing through a few lines in an attempt to gain clarity, if there is any to be found.

Yes! These poems were so beautiful and going to class felt like going to a book club. Even when I felt like I understood a poem before class, Professor Brisman always had interesting analysis and a new perspective on it I hadn't considered. Worth it even for non-English majors!
